<bill id="DLM999800" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" xml:lang="en-NZ" year.imprint="2008" bill.no="43" bill.type="member" stage="2" year="2008">
  <billdetail>
    <title>Waste Minimisation (Solids) Bill</title>
    <billtype xml:lang="en-NZ">Member's Bill</billtype>
    <repnote>As reported from the Local Government and Environment Committee</repnote>
    <commentary id="DLM1235800" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" bill.no="43" bill.type="member" stage="2" year="2008">
      <heading>Commentary</heading>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Recommendation</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Local Government and Environment Committee has examined the Waste Minimisation (Solids) Bill and recommends that it be passed with the amendments shown.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Introduction</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Waste Minimisation (Solids) Bill is a member’s bill in the name of Nándor Tánczos. We recommend that it be passed, but with significant amendment.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The bill aims to protect the environment from harm by encouraging the efficient use of materials and a reduction in waste, with consequent environmental, social, cultural, and economic benefits. The bill would reduce the amount of waste sent to landfills, introduce a levy on waste, and foster the development of product stewardship schemes. Under the bill as originally drafted a number of measures were proposed to achieve these objectives. Of these original proposals we recommend the removal of </text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>organisational waste minimisation plans </text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>the public procurement policy </text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>public organisation reporting </text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>the Waste Minimisation Authority</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>waste control authorities</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
              <para>
                <text>and target dates for waste reduction goals from the mandatory measures.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend new clauses under the product stewardship provisions, and new reporting requirements for operators of waste disposal and recovery facilities and territorial authorities. We also recommend amendments to the waste levy provisions. Under the proposed amendments a Waste Advisory Board would provide advice to the Minister and the Secretary for the Environment.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>New Zealand National, while supportive of waste minimisation, opposed the introduction of the original bill because the provisions were regarded as excessively bureaucratic, with high compliance costs. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>This commentary focuses on recommendations for significant changes, and does not cover minor changes of a technical nature. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The process of this bill has been unorthodox, but productive. It has had two rounds of extensive public consultation and a high level of cooperative engagement from the Government and all the members of the committee. This has led to a simpler, more streamlined bill that we believe will result in effective waste minimisation.</text>
        </para>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Submissions </heading>
          <para>
            <text>We received 316 submissions on the original bill. While we were considering the bill the Minister referred to us a supplementary order paper proposing significant amendment. Those who had submitted on the original bill were invited to resubmit on the supplementary order paper. We received 125 submissions on the supplementary order paper from those who had previously submitted, and some from new submitters. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Overview </heading>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Title</heading>
        <para>
          <text>While the bill as drafted is called the Waste Minimisation (Solids) Bill, we recommend that the word “solids” be removed from the title since the bill is not exclusively about solid waste. It will apply to some liquid wastes, such as paint and used oil. We do not recommend referring to “recovery” in the title because this emphasises waste recovery over other objectives. We also rejected the possible use of the word “management” in the title, as it would not have suitably emphasised the waste minimisation goals of the bill.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Part one</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Commencement</heading>
          <para>
            <text>The bill would have come into force 12 months after receiving the Royal assent. However, we recommend that the legislation come into force the day after Royal assent, with the exception of Part 3 and section 60. Part 3 of the bill as amended would come into force on 1 July 2009, giving the Ministry for the Environment approximately 12 months to establish a system for collecting and allocating the waste levy if the bill progresses through the House without delay. Section 60 would come into force on 1 July 2009, allowing an adjustment period for waste plans under the Local Government Act 1974.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Purpose</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend that clause 3 be amended to emphasise encouraging waste minimisation and reducing waste disposal in order to protect the environment from harm, while creating economic, social, cultural, and environmental benefits.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Clause 5: interpretation</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend that the definitions in the original bill be amended in line with the other amendments proposed. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend that waste be defined as anything no longer required for its original purpose, which, but for waste minimisation initiatives, would therefore be discarded. This is a broad definition which we consider reflects the purpose of the bill. We think it is important to define the term “waste” in the light of a recent Court of Appeal case, which noted that the term as used in the Local Government Act 1974 is ambiguous. We note that internationally it has been found to be difficult to devise a definition of waste that is neither too exclusive nor too inclusive.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend that reduction, reuse, recycling, and recovery also be defined: reduction as the lessening of waste generation; reuse as using material again in its existing form for the original or a similar purpose; recycling as the reprocessing of waste into new items; and recovery as the extraction of materials or energy from waste, including waste turned into compost.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Clause 5A: meaning of disposal</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend that the definition of disposal be amended to refer to the final depositing of waste into or onto land set apart for that purpose, including the incineration of waste. The term disposal will not apply to the short-term deposit of waste onto land before its being reused, recycled, recovered, or removed from the land.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Clause 5B: meaning of disposal facility</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend that “disposal facility” refer to a facility at which waste, including household waste, is disposed of, which operates at least in part as a business for waste disposal. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Parts 2 to 10 of original bill</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend that Parts 2 to 10 of the original bill be replaced by new Parts 2 to 7.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Part 2: product stewardship</heading>
        <para>
          <text>New Part 2 of the bill encourages and in certain situations requires the development of product stewardship schemes, through which the responsibility for managing the end of the life of a product and the environmental impacts of the product is shared by those involved in the product’s life. The bill provides for official accreditation of product stewardship schemes, including voluntary schemes. A number of successful voluntary schemes have already been established. However, there are a number of problems including free riders, a lack of comprehensive coverage, and the difficulty of establishing effective targets. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Part 6 of the bill as originally drafted would require producers of goods to take responsibility for their products throughout the products’ lifecycles, including their disposal. Particular products would have been sold only if covered by a product stewardship scheme. Deposits, refundable or otherwise, could be charged by producers. We recommend that regulations providing these features be retained.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend that the product stewardship provisions be revised, notably by introducing means by which voluntary product stewardship schemes could be accredited by the Government. New Part 2 of the bill provides the means by which products would be classified as priority products, compulsory product stewardship schemes would be developed and accredited, and voluntary schemes accredited for some products. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Under these amendments the Minister would have the power to determine priority products. The Minister would be required to consult affected parties and consider advice from the Waste Advisory Board before declaring a product to be a priority product. The Minister would be required to consider specified factors when classifying a product as a priority product, including the possibility of significant environmental harm created by the disposal of the product and the effectiveness of any proposed scheme for the product. The sale of priority products would be regulated only where this was considered necessary to ensure that relevant schemes achieved the environmental objectives established for the product, and where the benefits of regulation exceeded the cost. These amendments are intended to ensure that product stewardship schemes are workable. </text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Part 3: Waste Disposal Levy</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The bill proposed a levy on all waste dumped at disposal facilities, set at $25 per tonne. We recommend that this sum be reduced to $10 per tonne. We consider this lower figure adequate initially, as it will take time for worthwhile schemes for waste reduction to attract funding through the levy fund. The lower levy would also be less likely to provoke illegal dumping. The levy would be paid at disposal facilities and then passed to the ministry by their operators. The levy is intended to create a dedicated fund for waste minimisation programmes; and by increasing the cost of disposing of waste, it could be expected to change the behaviour of those disposing of waste. The level of the levy would be reviewed by the Minister within two years of its commencement, and every three years afterwards.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Fifty percent of waste levy monies would be paid to territorial authorities on a population basis, while the remaining funds, minus administration costs, could be contested by any interested parties (including territorial authorities). The Minister would allocate this fund to waste minimisation projects on a competitive basis, subject to specified criteria. A Waste Advisory Board would advise the Minister about criteria for funding. Territorial authorities would be required to align their funding of waste minimisation initiatives from the levy with their waste management and minimisation plans. We propose these amendments to encourage co-operation between regional and district authorities over waste minimisation initiatives.<emphasis style="bold"/></text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Material deposited in cleanfills would not be levied under the bill, but there is provision for the introduction of levies for cleanfills at a later date. Waste deposited at landfills that are operating when the bill passes into law and were identified in the 2006 New Zealand Landfill Census would be subject to the levy. However, not enough is known about the number of cleanfills, which are inadequately monitored and documented, to include them at present.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Part 4: Territorial authorities</heading>
        <para>
          <text>Part 3 of the bill as introduced designated territorial authorities as Waste Control Authorities, and required them to be responsible for minimising waste. These authorities would be required to implement waste minimisation and management plans, and oversee and promote waste minimisation and management in their districts in accordance with the New Zealand Waste Strategy. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>To simplify the legislation, we recommend that these measures be removed, because territorial authorities largely undertake these functions already, and some of the proposed measures would be too prescriptive or too costly for councils to implement. Councils are already required to promote waste management and minimisation in discharging their responsibility for public health, and we consider them the most appropriate institutions to ensure that waste minimisation services are provided. The provisions in the original bill might also have removed the flexibility that currently permits territorial authorities to take account of local variation and to allow private industry to be involved in waste management.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>For these reasons, we recommend that Part 3 of the bill be replaced by new Part 4, which would transfer the waste management provisions in Part 31 of the Local Government Act 1974 to the bill largely unchanged. However, Part 4 places more emphasis than the 1974 legislation on territorial authorities’ encouraging and promoting waste minimisation. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Under Part 4 territorial authorities would be required to adopt waste management and waste minimisation plans (currently waste management plans under the Local Government Act 1974). The bill provides more guidance on the content of plans. Clause 43 is a proposed new provision, which would allow two or more territorial authorities to draw up joint waste management plans. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Clause 46 would give the Governor-General the power, on the recommendation of the Minister, to direct territorial authorities to amend their waste management and minimisation plans. This provision should ensure national consistency between authorities, and make sure that plans take into account national policy. The Minister would be required to be satisfied that the territorial authority’s plan was adequate to promote effective and efficient waste management and minimisation before making any recommendation that authorities be compelled to make changes. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Clauses 50 and 54 of the revised bill would allow territorial authorities to contract or license operators to collect, reduce, reuse, recycle, recover or dispose of waste, and to make bylaws regulating the management and disposal of waste.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Part 5: Offences and enforcement</heading>
        <para>
          <text>New Part 5 of the bill sets out offences and penalties and provides for enforcement officers to be appointed by the Secretary for the Environment or a territorial authority to monitor compliance with regulations. Proposed fines range from up to $5,000 for preventing an enforcement officer from gathering information or conducting inspections, to up to $100,000 for breaching certain regulations concerning products, materials, waste or reporting requirements. Clause 59 sets out the defences that would be available to those prosecuted for breaching the Act, and these are of a similar nature to provisions in the Local Government Act 2002 and are consistent with the Resource Management Act 1991. Charges could be laid up to 12 months after knowledge of an offence arose. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The provisions for offences and penalties proposed in new Part 5 are similar to, but more comprehensive than, the equivalent provisions in the bill as drafted. The bill as introduced provides for some offences to carry a sentence of imprisonment; we recommend that no offence under the bill should do so. </text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Part 6: Reporting and audits</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The proposed new Part 6 of the bill provides that regulations can be made for the purpose of obtaining information on waste. These regulations would detail the requirements for operators of disposal facilities, operators of facilities where waste is received, and territorial authorities to keep records and provide information to the Secretary for the Environment. It would be used to determine the levies disposal facilities would pay, and to equip the Ministry for the Environment to monitor the impacts and the minimisation of waste, and for planning purposes. Before regulations were made parties that would be significantly affected would have to be consulted, along with the Waste Advisory Board, and a consideration of the costs and benefits expected from implementing the regulations would be required. This proposed part of the bill also includes provisions regarding the appointment of auditors and their powers to monitor certain facilities to determine the amount of levy to be paid or the records to be kept. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend that new Part 6 partially replace Part 9 of the bill as drafted, which includes provisions for public organisations to report on material used, waste generated, and waste disposed. These requirements would be costly, and the collection of this information is already required for other purposes. New Part 6 would improve the collection of national data, including information on how territorial authorities spent monies from the waste disposal levy.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Part 7: Waste Advisory Board</heading>
        <para>
          <text>Under Part 2 of the bill as introduced a Waste Minimisation Authority with between eight and ten members appointed by the Minister would be created as a Crown Entity under the Public Finance Act 1989. The authority would have various  responsibilities including promoting and encouraging waste minimisation, advising the Minister, monitoring waste generation and waste minimisation efforts, facilitating the New Zealand Waste Strategy, and updating the New Zealand Waste Strategy at least five-yearly. The authority would be required to give effect to Government policy and to administer the waste disposal levy. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend that Part 2 be replaced by new Part 7, which would establish a Waste Advisory Board, with a narrower role than that proposed for the Waste Minimisation Authority. The board would provide advice on waste minimisation to the Minister and to the Secretary for the Environment upon request. The Minister would be required to seek the board’s advice on a number of matters, including declaring a product to be a priority product, making guidelines about product stewardship schemes, and setting criteria on how the contestable portion of the levy fund would be allocated. The Minister would set the terms of reference for the board, and appoint four to eight members, one as chairperson. Anyone would be able to nominate members for the Minister’s consideration. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend these changes because we recognise that the Ministry for the Environment is best placed to coordinate waste-related measures, and under the bill its capability and profile in this area would be increased. National issues could be dealt with and policy decisions relating to waste could be made by the Ministry. Establishing an authority as suggested in the bill as drafted might lead to the separation of waste issues from environmental issues such as climate change, which we consider undesirable. The Ministry could develop waste minimisation policy alongside policy on other environmental issues.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Organisational waste minimisation plans</heading>
        <para>
          <text>Part 7 of the bill as introduced would require all New Zealand businesses to implement waste minimisation plans by 2016. We recommend that such plans not be included in the amended bill, as they would be too burdensome. Nevertheless, we commend businesses that have introduced such plans voluntarily.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Public procurement</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend the removal of the requirement in the bill for public organisations to procure goods on the basis of their durability, potential to be reused or recycled, or incorporation of reused and recycled materials. Pricing would be allowed to influence procurement only if the item in question cost at least 33 percent more than the least expensive comparable item. This policy would have demonstrated commitment to the New Zealand Waste Strategy, but we are concerned that it would have been too costly, and would have required enforcement. Other Government programmes such as Govt<superscript>3</superscript> have similar objectives on a voluntary basis.<footnote id="DLM1235801"><para><text>The Govt<superscript>3</superscript> initiative enables government agencies to become more sustainable by focusing on waste minimisation, sustainable buildings, transport, office consumables, and procurement.</text></para></footnote> </text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.appendix>
        <heading>Appendix</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee process</heading>
          <para>
            <text>The Waste Minimisation (Solids) Bill was referred to the committee on 14 June 2006. The closing date for submissions was 1 September 2006. We received and considered 316 submissions from interested groups and individuals. We heard 124 submissions. Those who had submitted on the original bill were invited to resubmit on a supplementary order paper that the Government introduced. We received 125 submissions on the supplementary order paper from those who had previously submitted and from some new submitters. We heard 60 of these additional submissions.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We received advice from the Ministry for the Environment and the Parliamentary Commissioner for the Environment. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee membership</heading>
          <para>
